SHOW DATABASES; is an SQL command used to display all databases present in your MySQL server.

| Database             | Meaning                                                             |
| -------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `information_schema` | System database storing metadata about tables, columns, users, etc. |
| `mysql`              | MySQL internal database for users, passwords, permissions           |
| `performance_schema` | Stores MySQL performance and monitoring information                 |
| `practice_db`        | Your own created database                                           |
| `sys`                | Helper database for analyzing MySQL performance                     |


---

Simple explanation

Think of MySQL like a cupboard.

Database = separate folder
Table = sheets/files inside folder

Example:

MySQL Server
 ├── practice_db
 │     ├── courses
 │     ├── enrollments
 │     └── university_students
 │
 ├── mysql
 ├── sys
 └── performance_schema


Important databases
practice_db

This is my working database.

I created tables here like:

courses
enrollments
university_students
System databases

These are automatically created by MySQL.

mysql

Stores:

usernames
passwords
permissions
information_schema

Stores information about:

tables
columns
keys
databases
performance_schema

Used for:

monitoring
performance tuning
sys

Provides easy performance reports.

Common SQL commands
Show databases
SHOW DATABASES;
Use a database
USE practice_db;
Show tables inside database
SHOW TABLES;
